German colonial rule varied vastly in its policies and administration across diverse geographical regions. Educational provision in these colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they encountered a significant population of educated and literate Africans. Similarly, the education initiatives in Kamerun and other colonies were commended by contemporary authors. In contrast, South West Africa (present-day Namibia) experienced a starkly different situation. Unlike in East Africa, where the government actively participated in the education of natives, in South West Africa, the responsibility for educating the natives was largely delegated to missionary societies with limited government support. However, the government did invest considerable resources in the education of Europeans, establishing a state school system and extensively supporting and regulating missionary schools. These policies had lasting effects on South West Africa, even after the end of German rule. While other German colonies boasted a substantial number of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa, "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to the unique experience of South West Africa. This paper aims to explore these factors and focus on new research into the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans.

There is a wealth of literature on education during the German colonial period, much of it in German and written in the early 20th century, during or immediately after the period of German colonial rule. Early works largely described the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later English writings expanded this discourse through comparative studies of education across various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects. These studies highlighted significant differences in educational systems among the colonies. Cohen’s study on education in South West Africa and East Africa is particularly notable. Cohen compares the educational systems of these two colonies and discusses the factors that account for their differences. According to Cohen, the substantial settler population in South West Africa contributes to the distinctive aspects of its educational system.

Compared to other German colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately friendly climate, though much of its territory is arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected these mild conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, compared to only 5,336 in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The evolution of popular music has seen an explosion in genres over the past century, making it challenging to enumerate them all. Each genre—such as rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk—has spawned numerous sub-genres and sub-sub-genres. Among these, heavy metal rock has emerged as one of the most diverse and expressive genres within popular music over the past four decades. Its expressiveness is evident through a wide range of emotions, predominantly on the darker side. Its diversity is marked by the early recognition of the genre's flexibility, which led to the creation of various sub-genres and sub-sub-genres, with this pattern continuing to this day.

Today, the heavy metal genre has evolved to encompass so many niches that defining it precisely is difficult. It has absorbed themes from other genres but has its roots somewhere. To comprehend the metal music prevalent today, one must first understand the essence of the metal movement—why it is considered a movement rather than just a genre.

Metal, in many ways, is defined by its darker tones. It is often referred to as the "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more intensity, and more theatricality. Performers in metal bands exhibit advanced instrumental skills, which are evident in their music. Additionally, metal is often associated with the use of drugs, particularly during the psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70s. These substances were used to create otherworldly records, serving as a vehicle for artistic expression. The genre possesses dark, visceral qualities that were relatively new to the music scene, providing an emotional depth often lacking in popular music. Later generations of metal have drawn influence from the Romantic Era's darker and visceral qualities. Lyrics like those from Helter Skelter by The Beatles, which express the darker side of the band, illustrate this. The song was a response to The Rolling Stones' heavier and darker music and is considered one of the early heavy metal tracks.

Before the Surrealists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was already crafting his own dreams, both literally and figuratively. His 1910 painting, The Dream, is not only a depiction of a woman in awe of the wonders she encounters in her dream but also a reflection of Rousseau's own personal dreams and aspirations as an artist. Throughout his career, he dreamt of recognition, acceptance, and praise from other artists and art enthusiasts, facing an internal conflict between conforming to or mimicking established painting styles to gain acceptance or staying true to his unique creative vision. The Dream encapsulates this lifelong internal struggle.

To fully understand The Dream, we must first be aware of Rousseau's background. Born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval, northwest France, Rousseau's father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer. He received no formal art training but worked as a gabelou (employee of the municipal toll service), earning the nickname "douanier" (customs inspector) despite his lower-class background. After the deaths of his first wife, Clémence, and their eight infant children, Rousseau turned to painting for comfort and a fresh start. Unlike his contemporaries, Rousseau did not idealize or romanticize the peasant in his art; he was a folk painter with the hopes and dreams of the common people.

Rousseau's desire for art-world acceptance is understandable given his context. Lacking formal training and starting his career late, he was producing works alongside prominent, better-known artists of his time. Recognition for his art began to come around the same time Matisse was building his reputation. Jan Gordon, in the book Modern French Painters, notes that while they were competitors, Matisse and Rousseau differed in their motivations: Matisse sought to avoid painting in a clichéd manner, while Rousseau yearned to paint in a conventional way to be accepted by the Artiste Français.

Numerous great thinkers have posited an inherent link between ethics and aesthetics, as well as between truth and beauty. I contend that this is due to a fundamental reason. As John Keats observes in his "Ode on a Grecian Urn," "Beauty is truth, truth beauty — That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." While much of what we learn in life comes from education or experience, we often appreciate ethics and aesthetics without formal instruction, as Keats suggests. Both fields aim to describe rather than dictate. Our explorations of morality and beauty are primarily attempts to understand why a piece of art or literature is beautiful or why an action is moral, rather than definitive rules for evaluating or creating good art or moral behavior. Critiquing art or morality, however, often fails to fully capture what is truly good or beautiful. A discussion about the value of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might focus on elements like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but ultimately, these don't explain why it's considered good art. When asked about a favorite work of art or literature, people often resort to phrases like "there's just something about it" before offering more detailed explanations. I believe that both art and morality cannot be fully reduced to descriptions of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor puts it, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way...you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” Similarly, ethics possesses this same ineffable quality. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I propose that this elusive 'something' — this je ne sais quoi — is art and morality's most potent attribute, and it is this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics that forges a connection between them. Moreover, I believe that morality and art are so interconnected because we experience them most vividly at a noumenal level, using a Kantian term. They impact us deeply, even if the reasons for this impact cannot be fully explained. This connection is even stronger when it comes to literary art. As McKean asserts, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values...Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there.”

Germany today is a powerful, unified nation, with a distinct culture that stretches from the alpine region around Munich to the Baltic Sea coast at Kiel, and from Cologne on the Rhine River to the heart of Germany, and on to the Saxon city of Dresden along the Elbe River. Given this rich cultural diversity, it's not surprising that Germany, as we know it today, is a blend of various origins and ethnic groups. The name "Germany" itself is of uncertain origin, with different theories suggesting it comes from the name of a Germanic tribe (the Tungrians), their use of spears, or the Old Irish word for "shout". Early Roman historian Tacitus, in his AD 98 work "On the Origin and Situation of the Germans", described the Germans as an original, unmixed race who settled in Germany through seafaring, not immigration or mixing with other races. The Romans, while they did engage in trade and occasional campaigns in Germania, generally preferred to send their conquests there rather than themselves. As a result, the Germanic tribes living on the Roman Empire's borders traded goods and skills with the Romans, contributing to the development of what is now Germany.

I gazed downwards, my mind blankly taking in the scene before me. I observed the object of study without emotion, my practiced awareness declining to connect it to any abstract understanding. Thoughts darted in and out of my mind so swiftly that it seemed I had no personal thoughts; instead, I was merely experiencing an active and fluid perception of what I was looking at. Once, following the advice of an artist I had worked with, I bought a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." My lifelong desire to learn to draw had driven me to this book, which teaches from understanding basic tools to the brain's processes in interpreting lines. One technique it taught was to place a square frame around any image to simplify it; for instance, a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen connected to a dining room would become a simple bowl of fruit on a flat plane. At that moment, staring at the bowl in front of me, I couldn't imagine framing the scene. I was so overwhelmed and awestruck that I could only stand and marvel. Masters like Picasso (blue phase), Monet (greenery), and Italian Renaissance artists (rainbow of colors) had already set precedents for artistic perspective. Before me were the beginnings of my own work, the start of my story, "Work in Brown." My fingers touched my chosen tool, my muscles tensing and relaxing as my hand moved through space, my mind giving form to the most creative moment of my life. Water swirled serenely and clearly, flakes of matter breaking away and disappearing. My hand struck the toilet handle again, more anxiously this time, but the offending brown package refused to budge, stuck like a slug. Grip on the mop tight, feet planted wide, a green tie uncomfortably around my throat, I frowned at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter left as a message for bathroom cleaners at Rite Aid. A few more flushes, a few more moments of quiet introspection, then my hand reached for the wall, gripped the end of the toilet paper, and began wrapping itself like an oven mitt. Standing upright, then bending at the waist, my hand slowly dipped into the bowl, like a mother preparing to retrieve a Thanksgiving turkey from the oven.

Teenagers are perishing in car crashes. Multiple factors coalesce to make this a deadly trend for young American drivers. The National Institutes of Health reveal that a significant aspect of the issue is the immaturity of the teenage brain when it comes to driving dangers. Lack of experience further exacerbates the problem, leading to more fatal collisions, vehicle rollovers, speeding, and road departure incidents.
Teens are especially vulnerable when driving with peers, which is common knowledge among those with any sense. Research by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center indicates that the age of passengers correlates with the frequency of traffic accidents.
Several states, including California, have implemented temporary provisional licenses to mitigate teen driver safety, limiting driving hours and prohibiting other minors as passengers. However, these measures are insufficient as a group, as young drivers statistically struggle with the risks and responsibilities of driving. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman asserts that even at 18, teens are not ready for regular driver's licenses. Studies suggest that teens under 19-20 are inclined to take risks for the thrill, making it logical to delay driving until this tendency subsides. If we continue to grant driver's licenses to young teens, we will likely see an uptick in deadly accidents, potentially reaching alarming proportions as the current generation of teens becomes eligible to drive.
A reasonable legislative approach would be to maintain driver's education classes in schools, blocking anyone under 18 from operating a vehicle. Provisional permits could still be issued, with a required number of practical driver's training hours, based on current state standards (e.g., 6 hours in California). Since teen driving deaths are widespread, national legislation could effectively protect teens nationwide. This proposed legislation is not unprecedented.

After browsing through the Library of Congress's archive of Edison's early films, I decided to watch all 15 trick films produced between 1895 and 1901. These films primarily use creative editing to create illusions. My analysis mainly involved describing the visual style of most trick films and exploring the unique characteristics of a few later films. Most trick films from this era are confined to a single set, using a frontal proscenium stage, with no camera movement, and feature long or medium shots, adhering to the rule that one shot equals one film. However, a few films at the start of the 20th century did break these conventions by incorporating multiple shots.

A common trait among these trick films is that they are shot within an interior set framed by a frontal proscenium, with the camera remaining stationary. This style, borrowed from theatre and vaudeville, limits movement to side-to-side within the frame, as seen in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). Actors enter from the side and move horizontally, never walking towards or away from the camera or having the camera follow them.

Long and medium shots are common, with close-ups never being used in these trick films, reflecting the traditions of theatre and vaudeville where the entire performance was visible within the stage borders. This style also limits the dramatic or narrative potential of trick films, as they often focus on brief vaudeville-style tricks like magic or disappearing acts, with little story. Note that, despite the apparent single shot, a single "shot" in a trick film often consists of multiple physical shots edited together to create illusions. For instance, in The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), a closer look reveals that the physical shot with Mary's "severed head" begins at a specific point, although the film is perceived as a single shot by the viewer.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate supporter of the Republican Party. His background as a farmer and brief political career shaped him into a champion of personal liberty and government reform. His deep commitment to an agrarian society informed much of his views on governance, sovereignty, and the judicial system. Taylor believed that the U.S. had the chance to establish an ideal government system due to the absence of native traditions that could hinder its creation. He held firm beliefs in the interdependence of natural rights, asserting that their denial would diminish the value of those that remain. In his view, a government should be designed to account for human nature's inherent good and evil. Taylor believed that good principles should protect private property, promote agriculture, and discourage capitalism. He thought that a government founded on such principles would function fairly regardless of its administration, which would be driven by avarice and self-interest. He also advocated for a strong, limited federal government with powers explicitly stated in the Constitution, as an extensive federal government could become corrupt and oppressive. Taylor considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, as it more clearly defines the country as a union of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

Looking back at Figure 17, commuter log submissions sharply declined in the third month of the project. The reason behind this drop is unclear. In December, fewer people are commuting by bike or on foot due to winter, and students and faculty are busy with end-of-semester tasks and holiday preparations. The project's initial excitement might have also faded. To reignite participation, we introduced the Carpool Challenge Week in March, which boosted log submissions. However, the project faced challenges, including holiday breaks and the general preference for driving. To encourage alternative commuting, we offered various prizes, such as gift cards to local businesses. Larger prizes like bicycles or hybrid/electric cars could have further increased engagement. Even increasing the value of the prizes over time might have helped maintain momentum.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a financial instrument designed to mimic an index, commodity, or a collection of assets, similar to an index fund, but with the added flexibility of trading like a stock on an exchange. ETFs offer the diversification of index funds and the advantages of individual stock ownership, such as short selling, margin purchases, and buying as few as one share. While these perks are appealing, ETFs generally have lower expense ratios than typical mutual funds. However, there are drawbacks, like the necessity of paying commissions on trades, similar to stock transactions. ETFs also offer a wide variety of funds, but it's crucial for savvy investors to assess whether these claimed benefits, like diversification, truly exist and to what extent.

For this analysis, we'll examine the ETF IHF and compare it with its top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of its assets. We'll determine if owning a single ETF can match the benefits of owning a diversified portfolio of these 10 stocks, and whether there are better configurations of these stocks that could provide a higher Sharpe ratio or return.

To simplify the evaluation, we'll only include the top 10 holdings. We'll calculate the Beta and return of a portfolio composed of these 10 stocks, using their current asset proportions. The calculations are as follows:

From these calculations, it's clear that a portfolio of the top 10 holdings could offer a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, with a 16% increase. Additionally, the Beta of the top 10 holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF's. These findings suggest that a portfolio consisting of just these 10 stocks could yield a higher return with a lower Beta. However, we should also consider if these portfolios are statistically different.

To assess this, we'll determine the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% for comparison with the ETF IHF's standard deviation.

Dream-land is considered one of Edgar Allan Poe's superior poems. In "Dream-Land," Poe employs the term "Thule" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used this term to refer to an island north of Britain, considered the extremity of the known world by the Greeks. While Virgil did indeed use the term, another more contemporary source deserves credit, as Poe was particularly interested in German authors. This usage demonstrates Poe's familiarity with Goethe's work. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," highlights the similarities between their poems, concluding that Poe was imitating Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature notes that Goethe was a renowned writer of the poetic drama Faust, published in two parts—the first in 1808 and the second upon his death in 1832. In the second part of Faust, there is a short poem titled "The King of Thule." This poem describes a king whose wife's death after giving him a goblet leads him to drink heavily and mourn, eventually deciding to end his life by throwing the goblet into the ocean. The King of Thule's fate echoes the dark despair in "Dream-Land," possibly reflecting Poe's own struggles with grief and addiction. Faust was also adapted into a romantic drama by H.P. Grattan in 1842, just a year before Poe used the term "Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe refers to "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and uses the term "Thule" twice in "Dream-Land," framing the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as companion poems. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thule as dark, lonely, and haunted by dead friends, resembling the state of the king in "The King of Thule," who is also lonely and has lost his will to live. The entire poem reads as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe's world.

Goethe was a significant author that Poe would have known, if only through his admiration for Tennyson. When asked if he admired Tennyson, Poe praised him and would have been exposed to Goethe's work through numerous reproductions following its original publication.

In California, the injured customer, Jennifer Palmer, may be able to seek punitive damages if she can prove that the store manager, Paul Martin, acted with malicious intent. This would require showing that Martin knew or should have known about the potential harm of leaving the applesauce spill uncleaned for a half-hour, despite two employees having already reported it. Although Martin's actions were likely despicable, given the previous six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009, his failure to clean the spill might still warrant a punitive damage award.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, employee Rich Wayne informed Martin about the spill but was told that Martin was on dinner break and couldn't handle it. Another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, informed Martin at 5:15 pm, but again, Martin declined to address the spill. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell on the spill, causing a serious back injury. Prior to Palmer's accident, there had been five similar incidents reported. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages.

Under California law, punitive damages for a breach not arising from a contract can be awarded if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." If the defendant acted with ill intent to cause harm, or if their actions were despicable and willfully disregarded the safety of others, punitive damages may be justified. In this case, the court will examine whether to partially dismiss Palmer's punitive damage claim based on whether Martin's actions fit this definition.

Four years ago, I enrolled in an Islam course at CBC, where the topic of whether Islam is an antagonistic religion sparked passionate debate. This question feels more pertinent today than ever. Reflecting on the post-9/11 period, I've noticed a shift in American mass media's portrayal of Islam and extremism, ranging from hostility to extreme tolerance. For instance, in 2001, a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, with apparent Muslim heritage, would have been unthinkable. The Prophet Muhammad's biography has always intrigued me, as it seems to contradict his historical portrayal. While I initially believed Muhammad forced conversions and conquered tribes, his biography depicts him as a martyr and humble figure, with converts drawn to his teachings. This portrayal shares uncanny similarities with Jesus' ministry and miracles, potentially diminishing Christ's life and miracles by attributing them to Muhammad. Furthermore, the biography relies heavily on third-party accounts, which can make the stories seem less credible. My main concern is the attempt to elevate Muhammad as a godly, humble, and wise figure, despite historical evidence suggesting otherwise. If Muslims today knew Muhammad's true rise to power, I believe it would be challenging for them to maintain this image.

The teachings and beliefs that Jesus held during his time were initially discarded in the evolution of Christian thought. If we examine this historical trajectory in a broad sense, a noticeable trend emerges: Christianity has been progressively diverging from its roots over time. Today's world is marked by an increasing awareness and a trend towards progressive ideas. While traditionalists persist and resist anything outside their learned beliefs, their influence may be limited. Among Christians, a growing historical awareness will lead to a desire to distinguish the doctrines added over time from the original intent behind Christianity. This process could take decades or even centuries, but the inevitable result will be a significant shift in Christian history. It will involve a movement that strips away layers of doctrine, as if reversing time, until only the core of Jesus' teachings remain. This trend, once it spreads across the United States and Europe, will lead to a widespread return to the worship practices and beliefs of Jesus' time. While the church as an institution will remain strong, the diversity within Christianity will decrease, with greater uniformity of belief and practice emerging. This reversal of history in the realm of Christianity is not unprecedented; after all, Christianity went from being persecuted by the Roman Empire to becoming a pillar of that empire. Similarly, our country has seen a shift from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The future will see a similar reversion in Christianity, undoing the diversity while returning to the source. A key factor in this process will be interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically rather than literally. To understand what happened after Jesus' lifetime, we need to look back to the roots of the Christian religion, which are found in Judaism. By the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., Judaism was characterized by monotheism, divine revelation, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures. However, the Jewish population at this time was not unified and was divided into various groups, including Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

Upton Sinclair's novel, The Jungle, illustrates the inherent greed and self-interest of human nature. People, by their very nature, are inclined to prioritize their own well-being and comfort, often disregarding those less fortunate. The novel demonstrates this through various aspects, particularly the factory owners and managers. Their sole objective is to expand their businesses and factories without regard for the consequences. They are indifferent to any harm caused to people or animals due to their operations. Sinclair vividly depicts the environmental destruction caused by pollution, describing the "great plumes of smoke billowing out of the factories" and the "river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world". The workers are also subjected to harsh conditions, working long hours with little pay and no job security. The lack of worker protections or regulations during that era allowed managers and owners to exploit workers without consequence. The desperate conditions led to the formation of unions, but many were corrupt and exploited workers even further. The workers were effectively enslaved, working and living in appalling conditions, "dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers".

Many authors employ various techniques to evoke specific impressions or attitudes in their readers' minds when addressing significant subjects. Some methods are more effective than others. In his novel The Great Gatsby, F. Scott Fitzgerald employs a range of these techniques. He often uses unusual adjective-noun pairings to create a certain atmosphere around a subject. Additionally, he invests symbols with meaning and employs them for the same purpose. Fitzgerald utilizes this approach with several colors, including gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald assigns special significance to white/gray and red/pink, building up their meanings and then using these meanings later to convey specific feelings about important objects.

Fitzgerald associates white with elegance and sophistication, while gray represents age and faded quality. He establishes this meaning with consistent use of these colors at the beginning of the novel. Daisy and Jordan are frequently “in white” (8), and most characters at Gatsby's party wear white: Nick is in “white flannels” (41), Tom wears a “white shirt” (36), and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). The only exception is when Nick observes Gatsby's party, where he describes the halls as “gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further reinforces these associations by applying white and gray to mundane subjects and people: Nick works in “white chasms” (56), party attendees have “gray names” (61), Catherine’s apartment is part of a “long white cake of apartment-houses” (28), Jordan and Daisy share a “white girlhood” (19), and there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of ashes. After imbuing white/gray with specific meanings, Fitzgerald uses them to convey feelings of unimportance or uniformity. The first instance of this is Daisy: after a long period without significant use of white or gray, she is described as “dressed in white” in a “little white roadster” (74), making her appear less distinct and more like a uniform desire for Gatsby. Fitzgerald employs this technique repeatedly around Daisy to emphasize her uniform nature. For example, her fur collar is described as a “gray haze” (18) and she wears a “white” dress (115) before Tom and Gatsby's confrontation.

San Diego County's agricultural prowess is driven by its temperate, sunny climate, with crops like tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers thriving here. The demand for organic, locally grown produce is strong, with many community-supported agriculture initiatives boasting long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also in high demand. Some organic farms offer tours and recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching. This type of operation can leverage government programs to benefit both the environment and profits. Additionally, organic farming fosters greater biodiversity due to the absence of chemicals, but it also demands more labor and management to maintain yields. Furthermore, it can lack the scale efficiency of larger farms. Landowners might seek financial assistance or expertise to maximize both profits and habitat quality. The selected property is a 160-acre parcel in Potrero, unincorporated San Diego County, adjacent to the Cleveland National Forest, within the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion. This area has a high concentration of endangered and declining species, including the Stephens' kangaroo rat, mountain yellow-legged frog, various butterflies, California gnatcatcher, and burrowing owls. Originally inhabited by Native Americans and later used for grazing and wood production, this land is now being considered for organic farming. Government programs and a nearby organic farm model were researched to explore potential cost mitigation and wildlife-friendly farming practices.

Culture's impact on negotiations is substantial. Defined by what it is not, and what it signifies, culture isn't uniform or specific. Stereotypes like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are too broad and simplistic. A negotiator should focus on the cultural significance of the situation and how it influences discussions. When encountering a different culture, one naturally compares it to their own. Understanding foreign cultures involves studying history or recognizing biases, not judging or changing them. Acceptance and working within cultural boundaries are key, especially with a weaker bargaining position. Respect for traditions can help overcome cultural barriers and advance negotiations. Moreover, culture isn't limited to national identities; many companies have unique corporate cultures, evident in work hours, communication styles, and hiring practices. Some companies encourage employee philanthropy, while others limit it, highlighting the diversity within a society's culture. Cultural values, which drive behaviors, are crucial to understand. For instance, a culture valuing "saving face" makes public shaming unlikely, while a culture valuing hard bargains might delay settlements. Before negotiation, understanding cultural values and personal traits of opponents can enhance effectiveness.

The fool has declared in their heart, 'There is no God.' This statement is initially presented in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and serves as the opening to St. Anselm's argument for the existence of God. It is also echoed by Thomas Aquinas. Since both arguments defend the same idea and we aim to compare them, we must assume they both genuinely believe in the existence of the biblical God. It would be impractical to consider any other divine entity for the purpose of this comparison. While both arguments present valid points, neither offers a comprehensive basis for believing in God.

To explore this, let's first look at St. Anselm's core argument. Anselm advocates for understanding God through faith, suggesting that proof of God's existence can be found within one's own mind. He argues that since God is a concept we can understand, we cannot logically deny his existence. Although his reasoning can be complex and unclear, his essence is that God's proof lies within our inherent self-knowledge. This is often termed 'faith' in Christian texts, where one accepts something without irrefutable empirical evidence.

St. Thomas Aquinas, on the other hand, contends that God's existence can be proven through reason and empirical evidence, without requiring faith. This approach could be advantageous in spreading Christianity, as it would allow for conversion based on logic alone. Aquinas presents five logical arguments to support his view: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument essentially shows that the proof of God's existence lies in the logical necessity for such a being. If you have all but one piece of a puzzle, you can infer the existence and features of the missing piece by logical deduction.

In the fifth or sixth century BCE, a future figure known as the Buddha was born. Throughout his life, he renounced worldly desires and achieved enlightenment, giving rise to Buddhism, with Theravada Buddhism being its most traditional form. Now 2,500 years old, Buddhism has evolved significantly since the Buddha's time, particularly in Theravada countries like Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is celebrated. Although Buddha didn't teach any religious festivities, this ceremony is observed by both monks and laypeople. The Theravada Buddhist community has had to adapt and change its core beliefs due to both internal and external factors, ranging from friendly to hostile influences.

This discussion will frequently use the following terms: internal forces, which are driven by members of the Buddhist community regardless of their monastic status, and external forces, which originate from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are those that harm or intend to harm the Buddhist community, while benign forces are neutral but may inadvertently assist or harm the community.

First, let's examine the fundamental teachings of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists take refuge in the Three Jewels—the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma, the teachings of the Buddha, is composed of the Tripitaka (Three Baskets) of scriptures. The Sutta Pitaka contains the Buddha's discourses, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines the rules for monks and laypeople, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka explains Buddhist metaphysics, including concepts like Anatta (no self), Dukkha (suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Recognizing these concepts allows one to escape Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, and ultimately overcome desire (lobha), hatred (dosa), and delusion (moha) to achieve enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka sets out rules for both laypeople and monks, with laypeople following five precepts (not killing, not lying, not stealing, maintaining sexual purity, and avoiding intoxicants), while monks adhere to many more. The most crucial doctrinal tenet is the Four Noble Truths: life is suffering (Dukkha), suffering is caused by attachment, suffering can be ended, and the path to its cessation is the Middle Way.

The United States and Mexico illustrate a historical rivalry that persisted for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145). The peak of this rivalry was marked by the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, during which the United States emerged victorious, acquiring Texas and the American Southwest. Various conflicts arose between the two nations throughout this period, subsiding before the onset of World War I. The rivalry stemmed from differences in religion, culture, tradition, and material interests (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31). This is not uncommon among neighboring nations that have enduring rivalries. While the United States shares geographical proximity and rivalries with Mexico and Cuba, other Latin American nations have maintained favorable relations with the United States. Religious differences, similar to those between the United States and the Soviet Union during the Cold War, were a significant factor in this rivalry. The historical distrust between the English and Spanish, inherited by their former colonies, posed significant challenges to establishing friendly relations. Diehl and Goerts (2000) document 17 disputes during this 57-year period, most of which were territorial in nature, involving border raids and frontier issues. Schmitt (1974, p. 97) notes that the rivalry became less intense as Mexico increasingly depended on the United States, and it finally ended when American interests shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico in the late 19th century (p. 110).

Fifteen years ago, I was unexpectedly and severely disabled by a condition I had never heard of before. At the time, I was a nurse, a career choice driven by a deep need for security and stability, as I had lacked those growing up. The mantra "There will always be work, and people will always need care" was ingrained in me as I progressed through adolescence and into adulthood, despite my dream of becoming a scientist or journalist. However, at 46 years old, single, and with no financial savings, I was suddenly unable to work due to my disability. Now, 15 years later, I continue to live on Social Security Disability and have very little to call my own. Every day is a struggle, and my sense of security, safety, and self-esteem is constantly challenged. I've learned that while I may appear strong, true support comes from family and friends. Life's emergencies, both large and small, are inevitable, and no amount of preparation can overcome some challenges alone.

I firmly believe that we, as a nation, need to stop relying solely on big government for help. While I agree with the need for self-reliance, I think we should also focus on rebuilding trust and mutual support within our communities. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies did not succeed by going it alone; they relied on cooperation and shared resources. So, while I encourage being prepared with disaster kits and supplies, I also urge you to build connections with your neighbors.

The question remains: how and why do organisms evolve as they do? What constraints may influence the direction of evolutionary change? Although D'Arcy Thompson, in 1917, suggested that even the simplest organic forms are yet to be defined mathematically, recent advancements have applied mathematical modeling to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis, both in terms of ontogeny and phylogeny. Our study aims to use mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic change in Prunum, combined with experimental research, to understand the mechanisms behind the evolution of developmental change. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to identify quantitative parameters that can model hypothetical and actual shell morphologies. These parameters were input into the CerioShell software. We modeled hypothetical shell forms to interpret the limits of possible morphological change in Prunum. These findings are being integrated with experimental and descriptive studies to better comprehend macroevolutionary events in this group.

A shell can be visualized as a spiral tube that evolves through 360 degrees of space. These spirals, or whorls, revolve around an imaginary central axis called the columella. The rate at which whorls expand can vary, and each whorl is separated by a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl is the last one, known as the body whorl. The spire consists of all whorls except the last one. The top of the spire is called the apex, and the bottom is the base. The animal exits the shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be examined from apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. The typical orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing up.

To count whorls, view the shell from the apical view and identify the first suture. Draw a line dividing the shell into two parts. Count the whorls from this line, estimating a quarter whorl if necessary.

Shells can be considered a series of apertures moving through time and space as the animal grows its shell. The path of the aperture can be traced using the coordinates of each whorl's aperture center and its horizontal and vertical radius.

This trajectory can be represented graphically and mathematically. Once a mathematical model is established, parameters can be varied to modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

Indonesia's neonatal and infant mortality rates have been relatively unchanged over the past decade. Although the nation is progressing towards achieving many Millennium Development Goals, especially in water and sanitation, the advancements in child and maternal health are insufficient to meet the 2015 targets. The reasons for these shortfalls will be explored below, indicating a need to bolster the overall health system rather than focusing on specific interventions.

Indonesia has seen an increase in the number of births attended by skilled health workers, reaching 72%. However, this figure still includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot provide medical interventions during complications, which is why maternal mortality due to hemorrhage remains high. This suggests that progress in this area is superficial, and there is still significant work to be done. Additionally, the percentage of children under five years old with diarrhea treated by a health professional has decreased, and postnatal care data is incomplete, indicating concerns in this area as well.

Cesarean-section rates remain low, at around 4%. This points to another issue: while urban areas have a c-section rate of 7%, rural areas have a rate of 2%. This disparity highlights inequities in healthcare access, with services concentrated in urban areas. Furthermore, vertical equity is a concern, as the richest and poorest quintiles differ significantly in service utilization, with a 27% gap. This disparity suggests that the poor have more difficulty accessing healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

When considering ways to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the primary question is how to best address the lack of service. Should Indonesia focus on developing targeted program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system, without concentrating solely on pre- and post-pregnancy care? While programmatic approaches are appealing due to their targeted and manageable objectives and faster results, there are drawbacks to consider. One major concern is that investing heavily in specific health areas can lead to neglect in other sectors due to redirected funding and human resources. Moreover, running multiple parallel programs can result in service duplication, increased paperwork, and uncoordinated efforts.

Victorian literature is known for its meticulous attention to detail and focus on the upper-class society of the time. Two notable exceptions are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, which incorporate mystery and the unusual into their narratives, enhancing character development and psychological depth. Both novels often use dream sequences or dreamlike states to convey this mystery, with each book employing it differently. In Oliver Twist, these strange occurrences provide insights into Oliver's inner turmoil, his awareness of his surroundings, and his pain. When he relives the shooting in chapter 28, it is as if in a dream, highlighting his loss of control over events and the dire state of his health. The shooting itself is overwhelming for Oliver, his senses numbed and his despair intensified. The passage suggests that Oliver's misfortunes are not of his own making, and he lacks control over his life's outcomes. His inability to react or take control reflects a growing sense of defeat, possibly due to the influence of Fagin.

Two years back, I was part of an after-school program tutoring elementary-aged students. I did my best to assist them in whichever subject they were struggling with, although I excelled more in English and reading. I was approached by one of the instructors to help a young boy named Adrian, who was in third or fourth grade and having a lot of trouble reading. It soon became clear that something was off. He had peculiar issues with reading; he could pronounce some letters perfectly, while others he couldn't pronounce at all. Strangely, he was of Latino descent and spoke perfect English. We faced challenges until I met Adrian's mother. During a babysitting session (to keep the stragglers occupied), his mother walked in. She only spoke Spanish, and I, with my limited Spanish knowledge, communicated with her. It dawned on me: Adrian could read well; he just didn't know the English alphabet very well. I don't know if this realization helped him, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the issue of language barriers in schools, especially in California. It also demonstrates that the problem isn't always as apparent as we think. Even a child who speaks perfect English can struggle with reading. This is a known issue, so what's the solution? For Adrian, it was straightforward—tutoring in English reading, particularly the alphabet and pronunciation. But for many children who barely speak English, the solution is more complex. There's no one-size-fits-all answer. Combining various methods is key: dual language systems, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes—none alone will solve the problem.

Firstly, the dual language system is a valuable approach. It benefits not just children whose first language is Spanish, but all children. Research shows that children in two-way bilingual education programs outperform their peers academically. However, there's fear and misconception that it's a waste of resources and doesn't benefit the majority. This isn't accurate. If implemented as the norm rather than the exception, all children would benefit. But how do we make this happen? Requiring all teachers to be bilingual isn't realistic. Instead, we could have specialized aides or tutors who are bilingual.

From childhood, many of us are introduced to the idea of something greater than ourselves, something we can't fully grasp. Some learn about this through religious instruction, while others seek answers within themselves or their families. Some readily accept these beliefs, while others reject them, claiming there's nothing beyond our own thoughts and experiences. We all have our own ways of exploring spirituality, searching for meaning and light in the darkness. "A cardinal," my father said in response to my question about his favorite bird. We were sitting on our front porch, listening to the rain, smoking. He was thinner, his clothes loose, his hair thin. He gazed into the rain, almost lost in thought. I felt alone, scared, and unable to discuss my feelings with him. I hugged him, moved my chair closer, and looked out into the rain with him.

My father passed away in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The treatments had prolonged his suffering but not eased it. What was the purpose of enduring more pain and time? I wondered if God had stopped caring about me. I didn't pray. I couldn't bear to watch him die, so I stayed away. I wanted to remember him by his life, not his death. I curled up in bed for three days, waiting for news. No one called me.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is, as Ian Watt describes in The Rise of the Gothic Novel, essentially an "oxymoron for 'Old-New'," blending old and new elements. The Gothic genre has been both criticized and admired, described as having little depth and praised for its ability to evoke a 'terrible sublime' (Burke). The original Gothic Novel, Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, combined elements of old and modern romances to establish the proto-Gothic genre and a new method of storytelling. Walpole employed old theatrical elements and new representations of nature within modern novels to create what he termed "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre draws heavily from medieval Gothic theater, architecture, and traditions. Even in Walpole's time, the term "Gothic" was used to describe various peoples, styles, and time periods, often negatively, as archaic or unsophisticated compared to modern advancements. The fusion of traditional Gothic elements and the new, personal perspective of the novel contributed to Gothic's enduring popularity and its ability to seem both outdated and fresh to readers removed from the original time period.

One prominent theme in Gothic novels is chivalry, a medieval concept representing proper knightly training. In The Castle of Otranto, chivalry is both preserved and reimagined. Gothic authors, like Walpole, valued chivalry for its symbolism of bravery, honor, and competence, traits they felt were lacking in contemporary society. By incorporating chivalric elements and ideals, Walpole romanticized the "gothic past" and hinted at the future evolution towards Romanticism. Writing during a politically turbulent time, Walpole, amidst political turmoil and personal accusations, may have felt that the moral goodness and innate virtue of the Gothic era had been lost in modern society. This is evident in characters like Frederic, who embodies many chivalric traits, including being a prince, suffering from tragedy, and being believed killed by infidels. His description exaggerates the trope of the "gallant and courteous Knight" (66).

Supply chain management involves the series of steps for moving products from customer orders through raw materials, supply, production, and distribution to the final customer. The concept of supply chain management was introduced by Keith Oliver in 1982. It encompasses the planning, execution, and control of activities within the supply chain to meet customer needs swiftly and efficiently. Six key elements make up a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers employ these elements to deliver superior customer service.

Production is the initial step in the supply chain process. It is the cornerstone of the supply chain. Here, managers define the timing, purpose, location, and method of production. To understand customer needs, managers analyze the market as it is the primary indicator of customer demand. After assessing the market and understanding demand, managers decide which products to produce and in what quantities. They then choose the optimal location for production, considering volume and quality while ensuring customer satisfaction. Following this, managers focus on workload scheduling and equipment maintenance. Production is crucial in the supply chain, requiring meticulous planning; neglecting details can lead to significant time and cost inefficiencies. For instance, companies like Wal-Mart and Target have detailed policies for every aspect of their operations, from employee uniforms to receiving shipments, ensuring smooth and confusion-free processes.

The second key element in supply chain management is supply. Supply involves strategic decisions about a facility's core capabilities and outsourcing relationships. A company might have multiple production divisions for a single product, each with unique equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager must determine which division is best suited for each product's processes. Managers might also opt to outsource work to other companies, primarily to achieve quicker delivery times, improve flexibility, and reduce costs.

A sign in Burma, which is also known as Myanmar, reads "Hitler is alive." Ellen Page, the actor from the movie "Juno," stands alone on a street corner holding a cardboard sign with this message written in Sharpie. Burma is a Southeast Asian country ruled by a military junta that seized power in 1962 through a coup. In 2007, the country experienced street protests for the first time in a decade, led by monks, which earned the nickname "The Saffron Revolution." The protests initially involved peaceful gatherings but escalated into violent conflicts between the monks and the government. The government cracked down on foreign journalists, including a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai who was killed for being at a protest. The official death toll is 13, but a defected colonel suggests that many more people have been killed. This is not an isolated incident; similar atrocities have occurred throughout history, such as the Tiananmen Square protests, the Rwandan genocide, and Nazi Germany's persecution of Jews.

Duke Ellington's enduring influence on jazz music is largely due to his long career and his ability to direct his orchestra creatively. While Ellington's piano playing is often subtle in the compositions chosen for this assignment, he excelled as a composer in creating intricate pieces that highlighted the unique skills of his band members. He designed structures for soloists to improvise, wrote carefully orchestrated passages, and tailored his arrangements to suit each musician's style, fostering a cohesive and innovative sound. Ellington's mastery of individual players' voices and their collective ensemble sound enabled him to produce many groundbreaking jazz pieces.

The Grove Music dictionary describes Ellington's sound and innovation, mentioning "Creole Love Call" as a notable example. In this piece, Ellington uses the voice as a jazz instrument to add texture and color. This technique, seen throughout his career, is exemplified in "Creole Love Call," where the voice transitions between smooth and rough sounds and interacts with reeds, brass, and other instruments in a structured call-and-response pattern. The piece features six choruses, each with distinct solos and arrangements, showcasing Ellington's ability to complement his soloists' styles.

In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington demonstrates his skill in tight orchestration and tonal versatility. A call-and-response between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing combines vocal elements of Miley's playing with instrumental qualities of Cox's voice to create a rich, complementary sound. "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)" builds on these ideas, as Ellington effectively uses Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton's muted trombone to introduce the melody, further emphasizing his approach to tone color and orchestration.

She had always felt a persistent longing for something, a desire that remained unfulfilled. This sensation began when she was 14, around the time she entered her teenage years, and continued into her 17th year. By then, she had decided she wanted a person rather than an object, but no boy caught her interest. Several had shown attraction, attempted to woo her, but none seemed appealing. She often wondered about this peculiar situation, trying to understand what could cause such a reaction in a teenage girl. After years of contemplating, she had no satisfying theories. Despite her internal questioning, she lived her life, continuing to ponder her desires.

A day at home was typically peaceful, with her parents being gentle and calm, rarely arguing. They only disagreed when she asserted her independence and lively personality. She was the daughter of a serene couple, but her vibrant nature made her well-liked. However, today was not peaceful. As she moved from room to room in search of inspiration, she heard her mother scream in the kitchen. Rushing in, she found her mother on the floor, in pain, and instructed her to take her to the hospital. Her daughter swiftly helped her mother into the car and drove her to the hospital.

The hospital was filled with the smell of disinfectant and sickness, but her mind was focused on helping her mother. She quickly found help for her mother, who had fallen off a step stool trying to reach a high cabinet.

This research aimed to demonstrate that sticking to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score", is linked to a reduced risk of developing chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, and a lower risk of dying from stroke. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet, emphasizing more plant-based foods such as fruits, nuts, whole grains, legumes, and replacing saturated fats with monounsaturated fats and fish. It also allows for moderate alcohol consumption. Previous studies have shown that following the Med diet is associated with a lower risk of total and cardiovascular mortality, and trials have found it more effective than a low-fat diet for weight loss and improving cholesterol levels in overweight individuals. However, prior research did not focus specifically on stroke or stroke mortality.

This study tracked 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, without a history of cardiovascular disease or diabetes, who are part of the Nurses' Health Study, a long-term cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. Over six periods from 1984 to 2004, the researchers calculated an aMed diet score based on self-reported food frequency questionnaires (FFQs) that assessed nutrient intake over the previous year. More than 95% of nurses continued participating throughout the 20-year period. FFQ data was validated. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed through medical or hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. Cases without available records were classified as "probable" and included, representing about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormones were also considered, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To account for individual variability and represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed scores from repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for potential confounding factors such as age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Using Cox proportional-hazard modeling, the association between the aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke was assessed, with separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Higher adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a decreased risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (including fatal CHD and strokes) were recorded. Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk of both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States experienced a severe financial collapse. There was a surge in unemployment, a crack in the housing market, and many of the country's major corporations found themselves in ruins. This economic downturn continues to this day, necessitating questions about its origins and how to prevent such an event from happening again. In essence, the crisis was engineered by self-centered and naive political decisions that coerced banks and corporations into offering sub-prime loans to an ill-prepared and insufficient financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to back and repackage these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted, banks found themselves short on capital reserves and passed the chaos onto the repackaged mortgages, which in turn affected the broader economy.

The seeds of the financial crisis were planted in 1999, during the Clinton administration's pursuit of a second term. To boost his popularity, Clinton eased lending restrictions, setting the stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times warned in 1999, "Fannie Mae, the nation's largest mortgage underwriter, faced increasing pressure from the Clinton administration to broaden mortgages to low- and moderate-income individuals, and from shareholders to maintain profit growth." He foresaw the inevitable consequences: "However, the government-sponsored corporation might struggle in an economic downturn, potentially requiring a government bailout like the one for the savings and loan industry in the 1980s." This foreshadowed the repercussions of the imprudent lending practices.

Multiple factors conspired to send the economy into a spin. Among them was the new, complex mortgage structures. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were widely utilized in the years preceding the crisis, further interlinking various sectors of the economy with the housing market. This increased households' and financial markets' exposure to the housing market, making them highly susceptible to even minor price fluctuations.

The housing bubble burst, leaving financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities in distress. In 2007, the top five U.S. investment banks collectively held $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt, representing around 30% of the U.S. GDP. Consequently, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at bargain prices, Lehman Brothers was dissolved, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were compelled to convert into commercial banks under strict regulation. Fannie and Freddie, with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September 2008.

Exposition in storytelling can be both a joy and a burden. It's where you flex your writing muscles, captivating readers with powerful, spellbinding prose. However, it can also be the part of your story that sends readers to sleep or prompts them to hit the "Back" button. Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her screen when she encounters "Too Much Information" that isn't engaging.

Exposition, while a crucial part of storytelling, is often a challenge. The common adage "Show, don't tell" rings true, yet Dr. Merlin still finds herself falling into lengthy passages that lack action or, worse, provide excessive detail. Essentially, exposition is the voice in your head urging you to share background information quickly to move the story forward.

In literature, exposition involves relaying past events in straightforward language. In movies, it typically occurs when one character explains a significant chunk of information to another. The author, in this case, is the one doing the telling.

Consider this example: While reading a story, you find out that the protagonist met her love interest at a specific time and place, they got married in a grand ceremony, and her spouse was killed in front of her eyes. You wouldn't expect this entire backstory to be told over two pages with only a few lines of dialogue between the couple. You'd expect the author to delve into the husband's character, demonstrating his deep love for his wife through his words and actions. Similarly, you'd expect the heroine to show how her husband's presence enriched her life, providing insights into her thoughts, beliefs, and dreams. This detailed introduction would help you emotionally connect with the husband's fate and understand the heroine's character better.

In essence, you must provide substance to the skeleton of your story, such as "They met, they married, he died." As a writer, you must resist the urge to rush through these details. It's tempting to quickly introduce a new character with a mundane list of facts, like being in the Air Force, running a gas station, having a certain dietary preference, or secret dreams. Instead, weave these details into the narrative to create a compelling character profile.

I caught two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first, which was live this morning (August 13, 2011), was from NBC 4. The headline story featured a man named Shad Hostettler from Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife (they didn't mention her name). He was arrested, and they showed his mug shot, which was quite disturbing. The story only received about two minutes of coverage, which seemed appropriate given it was still developing. The next story was about an 18-year-old man named Travis Buyers who was shot in the Sharon Woods area and critically injured. There were no arrests at the time, and the SWAT team was investigating. This story seemed brief, and I believe that might be due to the fact that Buyers is a minority. I've noted this trend over the years: minority victims of crime often receive less media attention than white victims. The next story discussed a bullet hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter, which was determined to be a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers offered a $5,000 reward for information leading to the shooter's arrest. Another news item was about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus, where a dark-skinned black man in a hoodie sweatshirt was reported to have robbed the store. The coverage seemed to emphasize his race and physical description more than usual. The final story was about a convicted Texas drug kingpin, Rene Rodriguez, who had been sentenced to 300 months (or 25 years) in prison for conspiring to distribute marijuana. They also mentioned his Hispanic background, which I didn't find particularly relevant to the story.

There exists an unyielding, indissoluble bond between brothers. This bond is a complex web of feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, among others. Brothers comprehend each other on a level no one else can, and they see themselves reflected in their sibling. In times of crisis, the essence of this bond becomes apparent, whether it manifests positively or negatively. When these emotions surface, they carry significant consequences. Recognizing the emotions that stem from this fraternal bond means grappling with the repercussions they bring. When one looks into their brother's eyes, they see their own true self, not how others perceive them. Their true nature is revealed in their actions and the outcomes of those actions. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers examine this theme and the intense emotions that accompany it. In a detailed, vibrant setting, these two boys embark on a hopeless journey. In the climax, bitterness and intense pride collide, and only one brother survives. The theme is conveyed through the direct depiction of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions, as well as through the narrator's perspective, which showcases the intricate feelings experienced by the protagonist and their worldview, both of which greatly influence their actions. The protagonist's actions are driven by a primary emotion: pride. From their initial outing to their fateful final journey, the protagonist harbors resentment towards Doodle. He desired a brother he could teach various skills, like holding his breath, running, jumping, or navigating Old Woman Swamp. He yearned for a brother who could join him in races to Horsehead Landing or perch with him in the top fork of a great pine behind the barn. However, Doodle's fragile heart made it near impossible for him to participate in such activities. The reality was a harsh blow to the young protagonist's dreams. He even considered murdering the child by suffocating him with a pillow, yet his heart softened when Doodle smiled at him. This simple act gave the protagonist hope and revealed that his resolve to harm Doodle was not strong. Deep down, he held a natural affection for his brother.

The human brain is a complex and creative information processor. As technology has evolved from primitive to advanced, the metaphors used to describe the brain have also evolved. Initially, the brain was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. It's important to keep in mind that these metaphors, while useful, can also lead to erroneous conclusions.

The brain's information processing begins with sensory organs transforming physical stimuli, such as touch, heat, sound waves, or light, into electrochemical signals. This information is then processed in both bottom-up and top-down ways. For instance, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing combines simple details like color, orientation, and border changes to identify the object. Top-down processing uses previous decisions to speed up object recognition. For example, it can help identify a black box rather than a black hole.

Once information is processed, an attention filter decides its importance and which cognitive processes should access it. For instance, while your brain processes every blade of grass when you look at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually, but you might pick out your name in a noisy room. There are multiple processing stages, and attention repeatedly modulates the results.

For the brain to process information, it must first store it. There are different types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. Information is encoded in various ways depending on the type of stimuli. Verbal input can be encoded structurally (appearance of the word), phonemically (sound of the word), or semantically (meaning of the word). Once stored, information must be maintained. Working memory, which stores information for about 20 seconds, is maintained by looping electrical signals through specific neurons. Long-term memory is believed to be maintained by the structure of certain proteins.

There are many models explaining how knowledge is organized in the brain, including those based on how humans retrieve memories, computer science principles, and neurophysiology. The semantic network model suggests that knowledge is organized into nodes representing concepts, with nodes linked based on their relatedness. For example, a node for "chair" might be linked to "table," which can be linked to "wooden," and so on.

Aldous Huxley in "Brave New World" raises concerns about the impending dangers of technology and capitalism. Society prioritizes community over individualism and instills a pursuit of immediate happiness from birth. Citizens are pawns in a system controlled by the World Controller, who dictates a singular ideology. Analyzing the novel through Marxist lens reveals Huxley's criticisms of these systems. He employs Marxist concepts like homogenization and reification to highlight the flaws of the emerging capitalist economy. Capitalism is critiqued through the Marxist idea of false consciousness, where the common people lack understanding of their economic relationships, focused instead on personal gain due to ideological control. The conditioning of citizens, such as through hypnopædia, enforces a desire to consume and indulge, manipulated by the World Controller. Hegemony, where one class dominates another, is evident as lower classes are unaware of their manipulation, while higher classes, like Alphas and Betas, accept their positions. Relationships in Brave New World lack depth, with characters' interactions being superficial and focused on physical attributes, suggesting that technology and capitalism stifle free will and expression. Love and extreme emotions are absent, and societal complacency indicates a capitalist-induced obedience.

I've been a student at University Park for roughly two and a half years, which equates to four and a half semesters. Navigating around campus can be challenging for many, including myself. During my freshmen year, I resided in an East Halls dorm room, ironically located at the farthest eastern point of the campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traversing from Stuart Hall to classes at various locations such as the Willard building, which is centrally located, could take up to 25 minutes on foot, especially during bad weather, a common occurrence in State College. I talked to an alumnus who informed me that not long ago, the East Halls dorms were separated from the main campus by vast tracts of unused land. Today, this empty space has been transformed into sports fields, new buildings like the Creamery and health services, and is now surrounded by apartments. As the campus continues to grow, the problem of mobility becomes increasingly more difficult. What is the ideal solution? On a college campus, it would be a bicycle. However, a bicycle alone cannot solve the problem. Students must utilize them, and the campus must be designed to accommodate cyclists.

I discussed this with a friend who recently restarted bicycling after a several-year break. He said, "Bikes are great. For a few years, it wasn’t trendy to ride a bike, but it's the only viable way to get around." Besides being good for one's health, bicycling is the most efficient mode of transportation. A bowl of oatmeal and some physical exertion can cover 30 miles or more. Like many of my peers, I now live off-campus, as far from the campus center as some dorms. The best decision I made this year was to buy a bike. Classes in Thomas building, roughly a 25-minute walk from my home, can be reached in just 5 minutes by bike, if pedaled quickly. The main issue is that Pollock Road, the direct route to Thomas building from my house, isn't always easy to navigate, whether by bike or on foot. While walking has its merits, I'm too busy to do so. Without my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would add an additional 30-40 minutes to my daily routine, totaling over two and a half hours per week. Adding the time spent walking to and from other classes, appointments, and other activities, would amount to more time than I can afford.
